    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That sounds like a good start. I think some of my students might get confused and ask why we don't just call it \"procedural due process\" instead, since that's what the text actually says. Can you explain the difference for me, but keep the focus on why the substantive side is more important for protecting people's rights?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Procedural due process\" ensures the government follows fair steps before taking away your life, liberty, or property, while \"substantive due process\" goes a step further by protecting the actual **content** of your rights against government overreach. The substantive side is far more critical for civil liberties because it allows the Constitution to shield fundamental human dignity from laws that are simply unjust, even if the government followed all the proper legal procedures. Without this doctrine, a tyrannical legislature could technically pass any law, no matter how it侵犯了 personal autonomy, as long as the paperwork was done correctly.",
      "source": "target",
